    <section id="tips" class="tips-section-hi678">
        <div class="container-wrapper-cd901">
            <h2 class="section-title-ef234">Furniture Care Tips</h2>
            <div class="tips-grid-jk901">
                <div class="tip-card-lm234">
                    <h3>Daily Maintenance</h3>
                    <p>Dust furniture regularly with a soft, dry cloth. Avoid harsh chemicals and always dust in the direction of the wood grain. Use coasters and placemats to protect surfaces from moisture and heat damage.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="tip-card-lm234">
                    <h3>Climate Control</h3>
                    <p>Maintain consistent humidity levels between 30-50% to prevent wood cracking and warping. Avoid placing furniture near heating vents, radiators, or in direct sunlight for extended periods.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="tip-card-lm234">
                    <h3>Spill Response</h3>
                    <p>Clean spills immediately with a soft cloth. For water rings, try mayonnaise or toothpaste on a soft cloth, rubbing gently with the grain. For serious damage, contact professionals promptly.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="tip-card-lm234">
                    <h3>Moving Furniture</h3>
                    <p>Always lift furniture rather than dragging it. Remove drawers and loose components before moving. Use furniture pads and blankets to protect surfaces during transport.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="tip-card-lm234">
                    <h3>Seasonal Care</h3>
                    <p>Apply furniture polish or conditioner seasonally to maintain wood health. Check and tighten loose screws and hardware periodically. Rotate cushions regularly for even wear.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="tip-card-lm234">
                    <h3>Storage Guidelines</h3>
                    <p>Store furniture in climate-controlled environments. Cover with breathable materials, not plastic. Elevate pieces off concrete floors and ensure adequate air circulation around stored items.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

